      "content": "The most unvarnished argument they would present is that race, intertwined with socioeconomics, creates a baseline disparity in preparation that affects performance in high-stakes environments. They would argue that the concept of \"equal opportunity\" is a myth because the starting lines are inherently different for various racial groups due to historical and cultural factors. For instance, they might claim that certain racial groups have been systematically disadvantaged, leading to generational poverty and limited access to quality education, which in turn affects cognitive and professional capabilities. By enforcing a certain racial mix, they believe that the true aptitude of certain demographics is masked, as the focus shifts from individual merit to meeting diversity quotas. This, they argue, is not about leveling the playing field but about artificially inflating the representation of groups that may not have the same level of preparation or inherent ability to excel in high-stakes roles. They would assert that true meritocracy can only be achieved by assessing individuals based on their actual performance and capabilities, without the confounding factor of race, which they see as a proxy for a complex web of socio-economic disadvantages.",
